<div class="intro">
    <h1>Governance</h1>
    <p class="lead" style="font-size: 1.35rem; line-height: 1.45; color: var(--color-text-muted); margin-bottom: 2rem;">
        How decisions get made today, and how that is designed to change if this work
        ever earns broader use.
    </p>
</div>

<div class="content-box" style="margin-bottom: 3rem;">
    <h2>Where we are: one author decides</h2>
    <p>
        It would be dishonest to dress this up. <strong>Right now, every decision about Web
        Everything is made by a single person</strong> — its author. There is no committee, no
        vote, no foundation. For an effort at this stage, that is a deliberate choice, not an
        oversight, and this page exists to say so openly rather than let the question hang.
    </p>
    <p>
        Standards work earns trust slowly and loses it quickly. The fastest way to lose it is to
        pretend a project is more neutral, more governed, or more adopted than it actually is. So
        the commitment here is narrow and concrete: <strong>be transparent about who holds the pen,
        why, and what would make that change.</strong>
    </p>
</div>

<div class="content-box" style="margin-bottom: 3rem;">
    <h2>Why a single steward — for now</h2>
    <p>
        Early-stage specifications benefit from one coherent voice. A protocol designed by
        consensus before anyone depends on it tends to accumulate compromises that satisfy a
        committee and serve no actual user. Until there are real implementers with real stakes,
        a small, opinionated, fast-moving design loop produces a <em>better</em> artifact to later
        govern — not a worse one.
    </p>
    <p>
        This is the "benevolent dictator" model that has served many open projects in their early
        years. The word that matters is the constraint, not the authority:
    </p>
    <ul style="display: grid; gap: 1rem; margin-top: 1.5rem;">
        <li><strong>Every decision is public.</strong> Design forks, the reasoning behind them, and
            their outcomes are written down in the open <a href="/backlog/">backlog</a> and
            <a href="/research/">research notes</a> — not settled in private.</li>
        <li><strong>Every decision is reversible.</strong> Nothing is locked by fiat. A stable
            specification is a high bar (see the <a href="/project-lifecycle/">project lifecycle</a>),
            and most of the project is far from it.</li>
        <li><strong>Authority is held to be handed off.</strong> The stages below describe exactly
            how a single steward gives way to shared, then collective, governance — and what has to
            be true for each step.</li>
    </ul>
</div>

<h2 class="section-title">The governance lifecycle</h2>
<p class="section-desc">
    Four stages, from a single author to an independent body. Each one is <strong>gated on a signal
    that may never arrive</strong>. We are at the first stage, and honestly may stay there.
</p>

<div class="gov-stages">
    <div class="stage-card is-current">
        <div class="stage-header">
            <h2>1 &middot; Steward</h2>
            <span class="stage-tag">We are here</span>
        </div>
        <p class="stage-role"><strong>Who decides:</strong> the author, alone.</p>
        <p>A single benevolent steward sets direction, resolves every design fork, and is
            accountable for coherence. The guardrail is total transparency: decisions are recorded
            in public and remain open to challenge and reversal.</p>
        <p class="stage-gate"><strong>Moves on when:</strong> sustained, substantive contribution
            arrives from people other than the author — enough that one person reviewing everything
            becomes the bottleneck rather than the safeguard.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="stage-card">
        <div class="stage-header">
            <h2>2 &middot; Core contributors</h2>
            <span class="stage-tag stage-tag-future">If adoption begins</span>
        </div>
        <p class="stage-role"><strong>Who decides:</strong> a small core, with the founder breaking ties.</p>
        <p>Commit and review rights extend to a handful of trusted contributors. Decision-making is
            written down as an explicit process rather than living in one person's head. The founder
            delegates whole domains and steps back to tie-breaker, not author-of-everything.</p>
        <p class="stage-gate"><strong>Moves on when:</strong> there are multiple independent
            implementers or organizations depending on the specifications — parties whose interests
            can legitimately differ and need a neutral table.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="stage-card">
        <div class="stage-header">
            <h2>3 &middot; Working group</h2>
            <span class="stage-tag stage-tag-future">If interests diverge</span>
        </div>
        <p class="stage-role"><strong>Who decides:</strong> a chartered group, by documented process.</p>
        <p>A formal proposal-and-review process governs changes, with the founder as one voice among
            peers rather than the final word. Membership reflects the people and projects actually
            building on the standard.</p>
        <p class="stage-gate"><strong>Moves on when:</strong> adoption is broad enough that neutral,
            independent stewardship of the trademark, the specification, and the process becomes
            necessary in its own right.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="stage-card">
        <div class="stage-header">
            <h2>4 &middot; Independent body</h2>
            <span class="stage-tag stage-tag-future">If it outgrows any individual</span>
        </div>
        <p class="stage-role"><strong>Who decides:</strong> a foundation or standards body, not the founder.</p>
        <p>Stewardship moves to a neutral legal entity that holds the specification, trademark, and
            governance in trust for its community. The founder relinquishes unilateral control
            entirely. This is the end state for a standard that has genuinely outgrown any single
            person.</p>
        <p class="stage-gate"><strong>This is a destination, not a forecast.</strong> Most projects
            never reach it, and reaching it would require an adoption this one has not earned and may
            never earn.</p>
    </div>
</div>

